(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cairo - Egyptian authorities have referred over 300 alleged Islamists to military prosecutors over charges of terrorism and affiliation to a militant group which was behind a string of attacks targeting police and military.In a Wednesday statement, the state prosecutor accused the suspects of links to the Hasm group, which is widely believed to be an armed offshoot of Egypt's now-banned Muslim Brotherhood.The suspects are accused of involvement in at least 14 terrorist attacks including a failed assassination attempt against the country's former grand mufti and targeted killings of top military officers.A total of 144 are in police custody while the rest are on the run. Among them, a top Brotherhood politician Mohammed Ali Bishr, who has been in jail since November 2014 - nearly two years before Hasm emerged.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.